@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description:
The semanticscience integrated ontology (SIO) provides a simple, integrated ontology (types, relations) for objects, processes and their attributes.

This project provides foundational support for the Bio2RDF (http://bio2rdf.org) and SADI (http://sadiframework.org) projects. 

website: http://semanticscience.org
email: sio-ontology@googlegroups.com
mailing list: http://groups.google.com/group/sio-ontology

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: Every thing is an entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: entity

@graph.rdfs:label: is related to

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A material entity is a physical entity that is spatially extended, exists as a whole at any point in time and has mass.
@graph.rdfs:label: material entity

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A quality is an attribute that is intrinsically associated with its bearer (or its parts), but whose presence/absence and observed/measured value may vary.
@graph.rdfs:label: quality

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A process is an entity that is identifiable only through the unfolding of time, has temporal parts, and unless otherwise specified/predicted, cannot be identified from any instant of time in which it exists.
@graph.rdfs:label: process

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: has attribute is a relation that associates a entity with an attribute where an attribute is an intrinsic characteristic such as a quality, capability, disposition, function, or is an externally derived attribute determined from some descriptor (e.g. a quantity, position, label/identifier) either directly or indirectly through generalization of entities of the same type.
@graph.rdfs:label: has attribute

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A social entity pertains to the interaction among individuals and groups.
@graph.rdfs:label: social entity

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A social structure is a social entity which consists of relationships between two or more entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: social structure

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: is attribute of is a relation that associates an attribute with an entity where an attribute is an intrinsic characteristic such as a quality, capability, disposition, function, or is an externally derived attribute determined from some descriptor (e.g. a quantity, position, label/identifier) either directly or indirectly through generalization of entities of the same type.
@graph.rdfs:label: is attribute of

@graph.rdfs:label: organization

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A geographic position is the coordinate of an entity against some geographic coordinate system.
@graph.rdfs:label: geographic position

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A disposition is the tendency of a capability to be exhibited under certain conditions or in response to a certain stimulus (trigger).
@graph.http://semanticscience.org/resource/exam: solubility (to dissolve when put in fluid); fragility (disposition to break when dropped)
@graph.rdfs:label: disposition

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: information content entity is an object that requires some background knowledge or procedure to correctly interpret.
@graph.rdfs:label: information content entity

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A role is a realizable entity that describes behaviours, rights and obligations of an entity in some particular circumstance.
@graph.rdfs:label: role

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A function is a capability that satisfies some agentive objective, or (evolutionary) optimization.
@graph.rdfs:label: function

@graph.http://semanticscience.org/resource/exam: A nostril; the interior of the heart valve; the interior of a bottle.
@graph.rdfs:label: site

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: denotes is a relation between an entity and what it is a sign or indication of, or what specifically means.
@graph.http://semanticscience.org/resource/exam: the symbol '%' denotes a proportion in relation to a whole.
@graph.rdfs:label: denotes

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A material boundary is the boundary of a material entity which exists as a lower dimensional entity at exactly the location where its parts no longer extend into space. Every material entity has a boundary, and a boundary is the boundary of exactly 1 material entity.
@graph.http://semanticscience.org/resource/exam: the external surface of the window; the surface of the p52 protein
@graph.rdfs:label: material boundary

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An object quality is quality of an object.
@graph.rdfs:label: object quality

@graph.rdfs:label: process quality

@graph.http://semanticscience.org/resource/exam: a collection of cars has as a car as a part;a car has an engine as a part; a car has a piston as a part;
@graph.rdfs:label: has part

@graph.rdfs:label: biopolymer sequence

@graph.rdfs:label: start date

@graph.rdfs:label: end date

@graph.rdfs:label: process status

@graph.rdfs:label: completed

@graph.rdfs:label: ongoing

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: predicted is the quality of an entity that is thought to exist, as evidenced by some rational procedure.
@graph.rdfs:label: predicted

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A spatial quantity is a quantity obtained from measuring the spatial extent of an entity

@graph.rdfs:label: width

@graph.rdfs:label: 3D extent quantity

@graph.rdfs:label: volume

@graph.rdfs:label: compositional quality

@graph.rdfs:label: quantity

@graph.rdfs:label: has proper part

@graph.rdfs:label: has member

@graph.rdfs:label: is boundary of

@graph.rdfs:label: acid

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A base is a molecular entity dissolved in a solvent that is capable of accepting a proton (Bronsted base) or forming a covalent bond with a hydron (Lewis base) .
@graph.rdfs:label: base

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An isomer is a molecule that is compositionally identical to another molecule as a result of a different atomic connectivity.
@graph.rdfs:label: isomer

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An ion is an atom or molecule in which the total number of electrons is not equal to the total number of protons, giving it a net positive or negative electrical charge.
@graph.rdfs:label: ion

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An anion is an atom or molecule with a net positive electrical charge.
@graph.rdfs:label: cation

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An anion is an atom or molecule with a net negative electrical charge.
@graph.rdfs:label: anion

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A polar solvent is a solvent that exhibits a polar quality.
@graph.rdfs:label: polar solvent

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A non-polar solvent is a solvent that exhibits a non-polar quality.
@graph.rdfs:label: nonpolar solvent

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A positive charge is a charge where the value is positive.
@graph.rdfs:label: positive charge

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A heterogeneous substance is a chemical substance that is composed of more than one different kind of component.
@graph.rdfs:label: heterogeneous substance

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A homogeneous substance is a substance that is composed of a uniform type of entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: homogeneous substance

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A negative charge is a charge where the value is negative.
@graph.rdfs:label: negative charge

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An antibody (also known as immunoglobulins, abbreviated Ig) are gamma globulin proteins that are used by the immune system to identify and neutralize foreign objects. They are typically made of two large heavy chains and two small light chains.
@graph.rdfs:label: antibody

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An alpha helix is structural region of a protein that is characterized by 3.6 residues per turn,  a translation of 1.5 angstroms along the helical axis in which backbone N-H groups form a hydrogen bond to the backbone carboxyl group of the amino acid four residues prior.
@graph.rdfs:label: alpha helix

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description:
A beta strand is structural region of a protein that is characterized by a roughly planar sequence of amino acid residues forming hydrogen bonds between the N-O and the C=O  of another part of the peptide
and having their side chains perpendicular to the planar axis.
@graph.rdfs:label: beta strand

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A protein part is any submolecule of a protein.
@graph.rdfs:label: protein part

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An ionic interaction is a weak submolecular interaction between a charged submolecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: ionic interaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A protein complex is a molecular complex composed of at least two polypeptide chains.
@graph.rdfs:label: protein complex

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A single bond is a covalent bond between a pair of atoms in which one pair of electrons are shared.
@graph.rdfs:label: single bond

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A double bond is a covalent bond between a pair of atoms in which two pairs of electrons are shared.
@graph.rdfs:label: double bond

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A triple bond is a covalent bond between a pair of atoms in which three pairs of electrons are shared.
@graph.rdfs:label: triple bond

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An aromatic bond is an interaction between a set of atoms across which pairs of electrons are shared.
@graph.rdfs:label: aromatic bond

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A disulfide bond is a bond between two sulfur atoms.
@graph.rdfs:label: disulfide bond

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A dipole-dipole interaction is a weak submolecular interaction between strongly electronegative atoms.
@graph.rdfs:label: dipole-dipole interaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: van der Waals' interaction is an a weak submolecular interaction between an instantaneous dipole and induced dipole.
@graph.rdfs:label: van der Waals interaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A base stack is a stabilizing interaction of DNA and RNA between spatially adjacent nucleotides and possibly involving London dispersion, hydrophobic and electrostatic forces.
@graph.rdfs:label: base stack

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A molecular complex is a chemical complex composed of weakly interacting molecular entities, and excludes bulk solvent.
@graph.rdfs:label: molecular complex

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An acid-base reaction is a chemical reaction between an acid and a base.
@graph.rdfs:label: acid-base reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A catalyzed reaction is a chemical reaction that is facilitated by a catalyst.
@graph.rdfs:label: catalyzed reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A redox reaction is a chemical reaction in which there is a net movement of electrons from one reactant to another.
@graph.rdfs:label: redox reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An inorganic reaction is a chemical reaction that involves the transformation of inorganic molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: inorganic reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A decomposition reaction is an inorganic reaction in which molecule is fragmented into submolecules or atoms.
@graph.rdfs:label: decomposition reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A displacement reaction is an inorganic reaction in which a elementary substance displaces and sets free a constituent atom from a molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: displacement reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A double displacement reaction is a displacement reaction in which two molecules swap ions, effectively displacing each other to form two new molecules.
@graph.rdfs:label: double displacement reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A single displacement reaction where one atom is transferred out of one molecule and into another.
@graph.rdfs:label: single displacement reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A synthesis reaction is an inorganic reaction in which two or more molecules are chemically bonded together to produce a single product.
@graph.rdfs:label: synthesis reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An organic reaction is a chemical reaction involving at least one organic molecule.
@graph.rdfs:label: organic reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An isomerization reaction is a chemical reaction in which a molecule is converted into its isomer.
@graph.rdfs:label: isomerization reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description:
An addition reaction is an organic reaction where two or more molecules combine to form a larger one. Addition reactions are limited to chemical compounds that have multiply-bonded atoms:
    * Molecules with carbon-carbon double bonds or triple bonds
    * Molecules with carbon - hetero double bonds like C=O or C=N
@graph.rdfs:label: addition reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A polar addition reaction is an addition reaction involving polar residues.
@graph.rdfs:label: polar addition reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A non-polar addition reaction is an addition reaction involving non-polar residues.
@graph.rdfs:label: non-polar addition reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A free radical addition is a non-polar addition reaction involving free radicals.
@graph.rdfs:label: free radical addition

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A nucleophilic addition reaction is an addition reaction where a pi bond is removed by the creation of two new covalent bonds by the addition from a nucleophile.
@graph.rdfs:label: nucleophilic addition reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An electrophilic addition reaction is a polar addition reaction where a pi bond is removed by the creation of two new covalent bonds.
@graph.rdfs:label: electrophilic addition reaction

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A biochemical pathway specifies a series of biochemical modifications and transformations towards achieving some biological outcome.
@graph.rdfs:label: biochemical pathway

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A chemical reaction pathway specifies a series of chemical reactions towards producing some chemical product.
@graph.rdfs:label: chemical reaction pathway

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A chemical synthesis pathway is a pathway involved in the assembly of a chemical.
@graph.rdfs:label: chemical synthesis pathway

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A chemical degradation pathway is a pathway involved in the disassembly of a chemical.
@graph.rdfs:label: chemical degradation pathway

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A 3D structure model is a representation of the spatial arrangement of one or more chemical entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: 3d structure model

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A sequence profile is provides the preference for a character at each position of an abstracted sequence.
@graph.rdfs:label: sequence profile

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A metabolic pathway is a series of biochemical reactions that begins with one or more substrates and ends with one or more products.
@graph.rdfs:label: metabolic pathway

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A regulatory pathway is a series of biochemical reactions that lead to the increase or decrease of activity of participating molecular components.
@graph.rdfs:label: regulatory pathway

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A medical history is a record of the events of a recipient of medical care.
@graph.rdfs:label: medical history

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A binary compound is a mereological maximum sum of two kinds of weakly connected entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: binary compound

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A stereoisomer is an isomer in which the atomic connectivity is the same, but differs in its spatial arrangement of atoms.
@graph.rdfs:label: stereoisomer

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A diastereomer is a stereoisomer that is not a mirror image of its isomer.
@graph.rdfs:label: diastereomer

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An enantiomer is a stereoisomer that is a mirror image of its isomer.
@graph.rdfs:label: enantiomer

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An optical isomer is a stereoisomer that rotates the plane of polarization of a beam of plane polarized light.
@graph.rdfs:label: optical isomer

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A structural isomer is an isomer in which the atoms are joined together in different ways.
@graph.rdfs:label: structural isomer

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A ring is a submolecule with a circular topology.
@graph.rdfs:label: ring

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An aromatic ring is a ring in which the electrons are delocalized across all atoms in the ring.
@graph.rdfs:label: aromatic ring

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A heterocyclic ring is a ring containing a hetero atom.
@graph.rdfs:label: heterocyclic ring

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A homocyclic ring is a ring where the atoms are of a single type.
@graph.rdfs:label: homocyclic ring

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An ionic compound is a mereological maximal sum of weakly connected paired positive and negative ions.
@graph.rdfs:label: ionic compound

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: An allotrope is a structural variant of a chemical element.
@graph.rdfs:label: allotrope

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A carbon allotrope is a chemical substance composed of carbon.
@graph.rdfs:label: carbon allotrope

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: diamond is a carbon allotrope in which each carbon atom in diamond is covalently bonded to four other carbons in a tetrahedron. These tetrahedrons together form a 3-dimensional network of puckered six-membered rings of atoms.
@graph.rdfs:label: diamond

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: graphite is an allotrope of carbon which is a conductor, and is the most stable form of solid carbon.
@graph.rdfs:label: graphite

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: fullerene is a carbon allotrope which take the form of a hollow sphere, ellipsoid, or tube.
@graph.rdfs:label: fullerene

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: aggregate of carbon nanorods is an allotrope of carbon considered to be the least compressible material known, as measured by its isothermal bulk modulus; aggregated diamond nanorods have a modulus of 491 gigapascals (GPa), while a conventional diamond has a modulus of 442 GPa. ADNRs are also 0.3% denser than regular diamond.
@graph.rdfs:label: aggregated carbon nanorods

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: amorphous carbon is an allotrope of carbon that does not have any crystalline structure. As with all glassy materials, some short-range order can be observed, but there is no long-range pattern of atomic positions.
@graph.rdfs:label: amorphous carbon

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: carbon nanofoam is an allotrope of carbon that consists of a low-density cluster-assembly of carbon atoms strung together in a loose three-dimensional web. Each cluster is about 6 nanometers wide and consists of about 4000 carbon atoms linked in graphite-like sheets that are given negative curvature by the inclusion of heptagons among the regular hexagonal pattern.
@graph.rdfs:label: carbon nanofoam

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: chaoite is an allotrope of carbon that is slightly harder than graphite with a reflection colour of grey to white.
@graph.rdfs:label: chaoite

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: glassy carbon is an allotrope of carbon which is widely used as an electrode material in electrochemistry, as well as for high temperature crucibles and as a component of some prosthetic devices.
@graph.rdfs:label: glassy carbon

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: ionsdaleite is a hexagonal allotrope of the carbon allotrope diamond.
@graph.rdfs:label: ionsdaleite

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A covalent bond is a strong submolecular interaction between atoms.
@graph.rdfs:label: covalent bond

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A biomolecular structure descriptor is structure description for organic compounds.
@graph.rdfs:label: biomolecular structure descriptor

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A molecular structure file is a file that contains a description of molecular structure.
@graph.rdfs:label: molecular structure file

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: molecular structure descriptor is data that describes some aspect of the molecular structure (composition) and is about some chemical entity.
@graph.rdfs:label: molecular structure descriptor

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A chemical datum is a scientific data item which conforms to some specification, either for how it is calculated or for how it is measured, and is commonly used in the domain of chemistry to name and differentiate different numeric properties (both calculated and measured) which are about chemical entities.
@graph.rdfs:label: chemical data

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A molecule is the mereological maximal sum of a collection of covalently bonded atoms.
@graph.rdfs:label: molecule

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A chemical substance is a chemical complex of weakly interacting molecular entities, and may include bulk solvent.
@graph.rdfs:label: chemical substance

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A PDB file is a molecular structure file specified by the Protein DataBank (PDB).
@graph.rdfs:label: PDB file

@graph.http://purl.org/dc/terms/description: A collection of 3D molecular structure models is just that.
@graph.rdfs:label: collection of 3d molecular structure models
